  "footnotes": [
    "N. Syria (Aleppo): the northern corridor was dominated by city-states (Ebla, Yamhad/Aleppo) in the Bronze Age; Antioch became the Seleucid and later Roman capital of the East; the Hamdanids, Mirdasids, and Zangids based their power here; Aleppo was the entry point for every steppe invasion",
    "Coastal Lebanon: the Phoenician cities (Byblos, Sidon, Tyre) were the ancient world's maritime merchants and alphabet inventors; the Crusader Principality of Antioch and County of Tripoli occupied this strip; Lebanon was separated from Syria by France in 1920 as a Christian-majority state",
    "Damascus / Jordan: Damascus is one of the world's oldest continuously inhabited cities; the Umayyad Caliphate ruled the Islamic world from here (661–750); the Nabataean Kingdom controlled the Transjordan desert trade routes; Jordan was drawn as Transjordan by Britain in 1921",
    "Palestine / Israel: the biblical heartland of Canaan, Israel, and Judah; the Roman destruction of Jerusalem (70 CE) and the Bar Kokhba revolt (135 CE) began the Jewish diaspora; the Crusader Kingdom of Jerusalem (1099–1291) made this the pivot of medieval holy war; the British Mandate ended in the 1948 Arab-Israeli War",
    "Coele-Syria (Hollow Syria): the Greek name for the Levant between the Lebanon and Anti-Lebanon mountain ranges; contested between Ptolemaic Egypt and Seleucid Syria through the Syrian Wars (274–168 BCE) until Antiochus III's victory at Panium (198 BCE)",
    "Umayyad capital Damascus (661–750): the Umayyad Caliphate made Damascus the center of the Islamic world; the Abbasid revolution moved the capital to Baghdad in 762, reducing Syria to a province",
    "Sykes-Picot Line (1916): the secret Anglo-French agreement divided the Levant into British (Palestine, Jordan) and French (Syria, Lebanon) spheres, drawing the modern borders without regard for Arab, Kurdish, or Zionist claims"
  ]
}
